name: Tate Reeves
tweet: These are difficult days for Mississippi. We will get through. Mississippians are strong. We will emerge stronger. Stay safe and God bless.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: This storm was as bad or worse than anything we’ve seen in a decade. We are used to tornadoes in Mississippi. No one is used to this. Winds topped 200 MPH. The trail was long and devastating.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Our chainsaw crews and other responders are ready to roll anywhere additional resources are needed. We’re flexing to support local efforts. Local first responders have done an incredible job executing. It is inspiring to see.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: The Red Cross is sheltering families with nowhere to go. Many are in hotels. We’re pushing out tarps and water.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Tens of thousands of Mississippians lost power. We already know that hundreds of homes were destroyed or badly damaged. Meanwhile, we are facing an unemployment crisis—8,000% increase—that leaves many of these people especially vulnerable. Tens of thousands just lost their jobs.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: There were 12 or more tornadoes last night in our state—affecting almost every region. Two followed the same long, destructive, deadly path through south Mississippi.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: At least 11 Mississippians lost their lives from these horrific tornadoes. Injury numbers will soon go up dramatically.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: On Easter Sunday, we saw savage storms across the state. We are still in the response phase. We are just beginning the work of damage assessment. Numbers will go up. That said, here’s what we know so far:

name: Tate Reeves
tweet:
The Easter storms were catastrophic, but Mississippi will not be defeated. We know how to take care of one another, and we will. We know how to be strong and courageous in the face of terrible pain, and we will. We are resilient.

Briefing at 2:30 to discuss ongoing emergencies.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: To the people of Mississippi, know that you are not alone. The state and our first responders are working around the clock and will not rest until this is over. We are mobilizing all resources available to protect our people and their property. 3/3

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: This is not how anyone wants to celebrate Easter Sunday. As we reflect on the death and resurrection on this Easter Sunday, we have faith that we will all rise together. 2/3

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Stay safe and weather alert—it is a dangerous day in Mississippi. Please reach out to anyone who may be lonely today—there are lots of Mississippians who wish they could gather together but can’t. Please also remember the reason we celebrate. He is Risen!

tweet: Help is coming—more financial help than ever before. But it is too slow. The government can’t replace lost wages in real time. Mississippians are proud. Many won’t broadcast they need help. But a lot of them do. Please consider quietly reaching out to help a neighbor if you can.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: This disease is not fair. It does not hit the rich and the rest equally. Neither does the economic fallout. There are many across Mississippi who are struggling, waiting as we work to scale up our unemployment system to manage the 3,000% increase in claims.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: The faith, calm, and loving spirit demonstrated by so many Mississippians during a tragedy like this is truly humbling. You are daily motivating me to try and reflect your grit, humility, and courage. Live update at 2:30–detailed briefing on hospital surge plans. God bless.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet:
There are some new solutions in the works to deal with the historic increase. It’s going to get fixed. And we’re going to provide more help than ever before. 

Stay safe, and look out for your neighbors. Many need food and some cash to get by until we can get this right.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: You will get what you deserve, no matter when you get through. Your money is based on when you lost your job, not when they can answer the phone.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet:
We’ve increased the hours. We’ve increased the staff. We’ve increased the ways you can apply. We’re still trying to catch up with the massive numbers. 

That doesn’t help you if you’re trying to get through and can’t. I know that. We’re going to make it right.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: No system was created to handle that kind of drastic increase. The people on the line at the call center are working class folks. They’re trying, but they’re being asked to do 3,000% more work instantly.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: This is not just a pandemic, it is an economic disaster. We’ve already seen a 3,000% increase in unemployment claims in Mississippi. It’s never happened before. That is going to get worse before it gets better, just like this disease.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: The church isn’t a building. Easter isn’t about eggs. We will come together virtually around the globe, and personally in our families. Celebrate Easter next Sunday, please! Just be smart and safe. Christ is risen!

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: They’ve celebrated in countries where large Christian gatherings don’t mean you risk infection—you risk execution. They’ve worshipped on battlefields. They’ve worshipped in the wild. If they can do that, we can stay home to watch and worship on TV, radio, or the internet.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: A disease can’t cancel Easter. Jesus conquered death. Christians have celebrated the resurrection in even harder times than these:

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: We’re getting together on Facebook Live this afternoon at 4:00 to share stories of Mississippi’s resilience and even joy in this scary time. You’re welcome to join us! We are going to make it through this by looking out for one another. We are going to get through. God bless.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: We will get our economy rolling again. There are people whose lives and livelihoods are as threatened by the national economic damage as any disease. We will protect you too, to the best of our ability. We also have to take this virus very, very seriously.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: I don’t say this to make you panic, but we all need a healthy, educated respect of this powerful enemy. It is real. It is deadly. And Mississippi is uniquely threatened. Please be smart, stay home, and take care of your neighbors.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: All of those models assume people will socially distance and shelter in place. We are trying to prevent the health care system from being overloaded. If you could survive with quality care, we need you to get that care. That is what all of this is for.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: We had a pandemic plan and we’ve followed it. We didn’t have to scramble; we were able to be methodical in ramping things up. It hasn’t hit us hard yet, but it will.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: We have advantages. We’re more spread out. We’ve done much more testing than others.   We’ve gathered and studied the data.  We have great health care workers.  Our emergency managers are 2nd to none.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: We are #2 in obesity. In diabetics, we are #3. Hypertension #4, smokers #6. We have risks that other parts of the country just don’t. We are already seeing that MS has a very high hospitalization per case rate compared to other states.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: But consider this: New Orleans has a death rate that is 7X New York’s. Why? The demographics are different. If you are less healthy to begin with, this virus can be more serious and deadly. Mississippi’s population looks a lot more like Louisiana than New York.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet:
The national models project that America might have 100,000 to 250,000 deaths from COVID-19 if everyone social distances. Mississippi represents about 1% of the US population. That means, if it hit everyone equally, Mississippi would expect 1,000 to 2,500 deaths. 

Thread:

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: You don’t need to take the whole family to Walmart or your local grocery store. We need people to be able to get supplies while staying safe. Send one person to shop for the family, and consider grabbing food for a vulnerable friend. Be smart.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Many people have asked why it is essential for gun stores to be allowed to operate while socially distancing. You have the right to protect your life, family, and property—even and especially during an emergency like this. This is still America.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: It’s not easy to stay at home for two weeks. I know that. This is a safe way to protect your own mental health while protecting the health of your neighbors. God bless.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Stay at home except for essential travel with one exception: you are welcome to go out in nature on your own. Take a walk. Ride a bike. Run your dogs. Go for a drive. Watch the sunset. Practice free throws. Fish or shoot skeet. I wish I had the time to do so right now, and would.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: I’m asking state officials to work on an enforcement plan that might allow us to open those up for solo fishermen in some way, but those agents are stretched very thin right now. If we can find a way to do it, we will.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: We had to close our major lakes, reservoirs, and beaches because large crowds were gathering all over the place—on docks, banks, and in bait shops.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Fishing is a very safe socially distant activity. It is totally allowed during our shelter-in-place order. If there’s a pond, creek, or private lake near you where you can safely drop a line while staying away from other anglers I strongly encourage you to do so.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: There’s a lot of bigger issues out there right now: lives are on the line based on what we all do to slow the spread of COVID-19. This may seem like a small thing given the serious nature of the times, but we’ve gotten a massive amount of questions and calls on this one issue:

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: People like to talk down Mississippi or turn us into a caricature. Mississippi is stepping up to fight this disease and our scientists are leading the way.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: I’m inspired by the work of our hospitals and labs to get more tests out to the public and completed. That data has driven our decisions, and I’m very proud of how much they’ve been able to do.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: I share this just to brag on the Mississippi health care workers and scientists who are leading the effort behind the scenes to give us information that helps us protect people better.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: This is just the beginning. We are going to further ramp up testing as part of our “Identify and Isolate” model—based in large part on the success of South Korea. It’s possible because Mississippi innovators have stepped up. All credit to them.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: We have a population that is very susceptible to this virus. Keep that in mind. We have issued a shelter-in-place because we think we are close to hitting the worst weeks of this soon. Stay home. Stay safe.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Mississippi’s testing infrastructure has been exceptional. Now remember, everyone is at different points in the cycle. In Mississippi, the total damage from this virus is going to get worse before it gets better.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Everyone has hailed South Korea for their robust testing. They tested about 5,200 of their citizens per every million. We have now exceeded that metric in Mississippi. We’re at more than 5,500 tests per million residents.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: VA has done 15,344 tests. Their population is nearly triple ours. KY has about 1.5 million more residents than we do. We’ve more than doubled their number of tests. Every state is working hard—so no knock against them—but MS is outpacing the national average by quite a lot.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet: Mississippi has done 16,662 total tests. We have 1,177 cases. Our population is a little less than three million.

name: Tate Reeves
tweet:
There is plenty of bad news in a time like this. I want to share a bit good news. Mississippi scientists and health care workers have stepped up big time. They have been deploying a lot of tests, and our state is punching way above our weight. The numbers may shock you.

name: Tate Reeves
